A debt write-down in Europe is inevitable.
Berkeley — "That was just the Greek crisis," "That was just the Greek and Irish crisis," people used to think, but that no longer holds, because it is clearly a crisis of the eurozone.
To deal with it, it is both easier and more difficult than usually anticipated.
The economics of this crisis is quite simple.
Greece has financial problems.
Ireland has banking problems.
Portugal has problems with its private debt market.
Spain has problems in all three of the above areas.
Although the details vary, the conclusion is the same: these countries all have to undergo a painful process of spending cuts.
The usual approach to offset the side effects of austerity is to combine domestic spending cuts with a depreciation of the domestic currency.
Depreciation enhances export competitiveness, that is, using external demand to compensate for internal demand.
However, these countries are all members of the eurozone, and they do not have independent currencies that can be devalued, so they can only use internal devaluation as a substitute for external devaluation.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs to enhance export competitiveness and achieve the effect of expanding external demand.
Actually, these crisis countries have made quite a determined effort to tighten their belts.
However, one economic variable has not changed along with the adjustment of other variables, that is, the debt of the public and private sectors.
The face value of government accumulated debt has not changed, and bank debt—except for some debt owed to junior creditors—has also remained largely unchanged.
It is this simple fact that places the internal devaluation strategy in a self-contradictory position: the more wages and other costs are cut, the heavier the burden of accumulated debt becomes relatively.
The heavier the debt burden, the more public spending must be cut and taxes increased in order to deal with the debt of the government and its defenders (such as banks).
This in turn demands more internal devaluation, further increasing the debt burden, creating a vicious cycle that drags the economy into a depression.
Therefore, in order for the internal devaluation strategy to be effective, it is necessary to find a way to reduce the face value of debt.
Government debt must be restructured.
Bank debt must be converted into equity, and when banks are insolvent, the debt should be written off.
Mortgage debt must also be written down.
It is understandable that policymakers are reluctant to take this path.
Sacred contracts.
Governments are concerned about losing credibility with financial markets.
If creditors are mainly foreign, especially foreign banks, debt write-downs would only burden other countries.
These concerns are not without merit, but they should not lead to unreasonable conclusions.
The only options are internal devaluation or external devaluation.
European leaders must choose between the two options.
They unanimously ruled out the option of external devaluation.
But internal devaluation necessarily requires debt restructuring.
It is both unreasonable and illogical to deny this.
The operation of debt restructuring is straightforward and clear.
The government can issue a batch of debt with a face value discounted by a certain percentage from the existing debt face value.
Bondholders can choose either to hold out for redemption of their bonds at face value, albeit with a later maturity date and lower interest rate, or to accept discounted bonds with a lower face value than existing bonds, but with an earlier maturity date and higher interest rate.
This is not cutting-edge technology; people have done this before.
But to succeed, there are three prerequisites.
First, it is necessary to assure bondholders of the safety of the new bonds.
Someone needs to guarantee these bonds.
In the 1980s, when Latin American debt restructuring was implemented under the Brady Plan, the U.S. Treasury played the role of the "guaranteeing elder brother."
Now, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Second, countries must act in unison.
Otherwise, debt restructuring in one country would raise expectations in others, triggering a ripple effect.
Finally, banks that suffer losses due to debt restructuring must consolidate their balance sheets.
These banks need to undergo real stress tests, rather than the bureaucratic formalities conducted earlier this year.
If debt restructuring signals capital shortfalls, a comprehensive conversion of bank debt into equity is necessary.
If this is not enough, the government must directly inject capital into the relevant banks.
This also requires coordinated action by all countries.
Once banks' balance sheets are consolidated, it becomes possible to restructure mortgage debt, bank debt, and other private sector debts without undermining the entire financial system.
Now let's talk about the biggest challenge.
All of this requires resolute leadership.
German leaders must acknowledge that their banks have significant risk exposure to the debts of peripheral eurozone countries and that the situation is critical.
They must convince the backroom bosses and voters that guaranteeing public funds for debt restructuring and bank recapitalization is a necessary condition for internal devaluation; since Germany is urging other EU countries to adopt this strategy, it should shoulder the responsibility of providing guarantees without hesitation.
In short, European leaders, especially German leaders, need to make the consequences sound more severe — otherwise, disaster will be upon them.
Because that's just the way it is.
